# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: swc-compiler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] An **abstract syntax tree** (**AST**) is a data structure used in computer science to represent the structure of a program or code snippet.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] It is a tree representation of the abstract syntactic structure of text (often source code) written in a formal language.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Each node of the tree denotes a construct occurring in the text.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] It is sometimes called just a **syntax tree**.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] The syntax is "abstract" in the sense that it does not represent every detail appearing in the real syntax, but rather just the structural or content-related details.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] For instance, grouping parentheses are implicit in the tree structure, so these do not have to be represented as separate nodes.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Likewise, a syntactic construct like an if-condition-then statement may be denoted by means of a single node with three branches.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] This distinguishes abstract syntax trees from concrete syntax trees, traditionally designated parse trees.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Parse trees are typically built by a parser during the source code translation and compiling process.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Once built, additional information is added to the AST by means of subsequent processing, e.g., contextual analysis.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Abstract syntax trees are also used in program analysis and program transformation systems.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Abstract syntax trees are data structures widely used in compilers to represent the structure of program code.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] An AST is usually the result of the syntax analysis phase of a compiler.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] It often serves as an intermediate representation of the program through several stages that the compiler requires, and has a strong effect on the final output of the compiler.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Languages are often ambiguous by nature.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] In order to avoid this ambiguity, programming languages are often specified as a context-free grammar (CFG).
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] However, there are often aspects of programming languages that a CFG can't express, but are part of the language and are documented in its specification.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] These are details that require a context to determine their validity and behavior.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] For example, if a language allows new types to be declared, a CFG cannot predict the names of such types nor the way in which they should be used.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Even if a language has a predefined set of types, enforcing proper usage usually requires some context.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Another example is duck typing, where the type of an element can change depending on context.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Operator overloading is yet another case where correct usage and final function are context-dependent.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] The design of an AST is often closely linked with the design of a compiler and its expected features.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] These requirements can be used to design the data structure for the AST.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Some operations will always require two elements, such as the two terms for addition.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] However, some language constructs require an arbitrarily large number of children, such as argument lists passed to programs from the command shell.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] As a result, an AST used to represent code written in such a language has to also be flexible enough to allow for the quick addition of an unknown quantity of children.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] To support compiler verification it should be possible to unparse an AST into source code form.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] The source code produced should be sufficiently similar to the original in appearance and identical in execution, upon recompilation.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] The AST is used intensively during semantic analysis, where the compiler checks for correct usage of the elements of the program and the language.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] The compiler also generates symbol tables based on the AST during semantic analysis.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] A complete traversal of the tree allows verification of the correctness of the program.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] After verifying correctness, the AST serves as the base for code generation.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] The AST is often used to generate an intermediate representation (IR), sometimes called an intermediate language, for the code generation.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] AST differencing, or for short tree differencing, consists of computing the list of differences between two ASTs.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] This list of differences is typically called an edit script.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] The edit script directly refers to the AST of the code.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] For instance, an edit action may result in the addition of a new AST node representing a function.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] An AST is a powerful abstraction to perform code clone detection.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Let ${\mathcal {O}}=\{{\mathcal {O_{\alpha }}}\}_{\alpha \in \mathrm {Arity} (S)}$ be an $\mathrm {Arity} (S)$ -indexed family of disjoint sets of *operators*.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] If o is an operator arity $(s_{1},\dots ,s_{n})s$ we say that o has sort s and has n arguments of sorts $s_{1},\dots ,s_{n}$ .
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Fix S be a finite set of sorts, and ${\mathcal {O}}$ an $\mathrm {Arity} (S)$ -indexed family of disjoint sets of *operators*.
[src:swc-compiler/abstract-syntax-tree] Let ${\mathcal {X}}=\{{\mathcal {X}}_{s}\}_{s\in S}$ be an S -indexed family of disjoint sets of variables.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In computing, a **compiler** is software that translates computer code written in one programming language (the *source* language) into another language (the *target* language).
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The name "compiler" is primarily used for programs that translate source code from a high-level programming language to a low-level programming language (e.g., assembly language, object code, or machine code) to create an executable program.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] There are many different types of compilers which produce output in different useful forms.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] A *cross-compiler* produces code for a different central processing unit (CPU) or operating system than the one on which the cross-compiler itself runs.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] A *bootstrap compiler* is often a temporary compiler, used for compiling a more permanent or better optimized compiler for a language.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Compilers generally implement these phases as modular components, promoting efficient design and correctness of transformations of source input to target output.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Program faults caused by incorrect compiler behavior can be very difficult to track down and work around; therefore, compiler implementers invest significant effort to ensure compiler correctness.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] With respect to making source code runnable, an interpreter provides a similar function as a compiler, but via a different mechanism.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] An interpreter executes code without converting it to machine code.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Therefore, some interpreters execute source code while others execute an intermediate form such as bytecode.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] A program compiled to native code tends to run faster than when interpreted, while environments with a bytecode-intermediate-form tends toward intermediate-speed.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Alternatively, just-in-time compilation allows for native execution speed with a one-time startup processing time cost.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Low-level programming languages, such as assembly and C, are typically compiled, especially when speed is a significant concern, rather than having cross-platform support.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For such languages, there are more one-to-one correspondences between the source code and the resulting machine code, making it easier for programmers to control the use of hardware.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In theory, any programming language can be used via either a compiler or an interpreter, but in practice, languages tend to be used with only one or the other.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Nonetheless, it is possible to write a compiler for a language that is commonly interpreted.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For example, Common Lisp can be compiled to Java bytecode (and then interpreted by the Java virtual machine), to C code (which can then be compiled again to native machine code), or directly to native code.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Theoretical computing concepts developed by scientists, mathematicians, and engineers formed the basis of digital modern computing development during World War II.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Primitive binary languages evolved because digital devices only understand ones and zeros and the circuit patterns in the underlying machine architecture.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In the late 1940s, assembly languages were created to offer a more workable abstraction of the computer architectures.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Limited memory capacity of early computers led to substantial technical challenges when the first compilers were designed.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Therefore, the compiling process needed to be divided into several small programs.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The front end programs produce the analysis products used by the back end programs to generate target code.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] As computer technology provided more resources, compiler designs could align better with the compiling process.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] It is usually more productive for a programmer to use a high-level language, so the development of high-level languages followed naturally from the abilities offered by digital computers.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] High-level languages are formal languages that are strictly defined by their syntax and semantics which form the high-level language architecture.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The sentences in a language may be defined by a set of rules called a grammar.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Backus–Naur form (BNF) describes the syntax of "sentences" of a language.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] It was developed by John Backus and used for the syntax of Algol 60.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The ideas derive from the context-free grammar concepts by linguist Noam Chomsky.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] "BNF and its extensions have become standard tools for describing the syntax of programming notations.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Between 1942 and 1945, Konrad Zuse designed the first (algorithmic) programming language for computers named *Plankalkül* ("Plan Calculus").
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Zuse also envisioned a *Planfertigungsgerät* ("Plan assembly device") to automatically translate the mathematical formulation of a program into machine-readable punched film stock.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] While no implementation occurred until the 1970s, it presented concepts later seen in APL designed by Ken Iverson in the late 1950s.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] APL is a language for mathematical computations.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Between 1949 and 1951, Heinz Rutishauser proposed Superplan, a high-level language and automatic translator.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] His ideas were later refined by Friedrich L.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Compiler technology evolved from the need for a strictly defined transformation of the high-level source program into a low-level target program for the digital computer.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The compiler could be viewed as a front end to deal with the analysis of the source code and a back end to synthesize the analysis into the target code.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Optimization between the front end and back end could produce more efficient target code.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Early operating systems and software were written in assembly language.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In the 1960s and early 1970s, the use of high-level languages for system programming was still controversial due to resource limitations.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] However, several research and industry efforts began the shift toward high-level systems programming languages, for example, BCPL, BLISS, B, and C.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language) designed in 1966 by Martin Richards at the University of Cambridge was originally developed as a compiler writing tool.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Several compilers have been implemented, Richards' book provides insights to the language and its compiler.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] BCPL was not only an influential systems programming language that is still used in research but also provided a basis for the design of B and C languages.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] BLISS (Basic Language for Implementation of System Software) was developed for a Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-10 computer by W.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Wulf's Carnegie Mellon University (CMU) research team.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The CMU team went on to develop BLISS-11 compiler one year later in 1970.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Multics (Multiplexed Information and Computing Service), a time-sharing operating system project, involved MIT, Bell Labs, General Electric (later Honeywell) and was led by Fernando Corbató from MIT.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Multics was written in the PL/I language developed by IBM and IBM User Group.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] IBM's goal was to satisfy business, scientific, and systems programming requirements.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] There were other languages that could have been considered but PL/I offered the most complete solution even though it had not been implemented.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For the first few years of the Multics project, a subset of the language could be compiled to assembly language with the Early PL/I (EPL) compiler by Doug McIlory and Bob Morris from Bell Labs.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] EPL supported the project until a boot-strapping compiler for the full PL/I could be developed.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Bell Labs left the Multics project in 1969, and developed a system programming language B based on BCPL concepts, written by Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Ritchie created a boot-strapping compiler for B and wrote Unics (Uniplexed Information and Computing Service) operating system for a PDP-7 in B.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Bell Labs started the development and expansion of C based on B and BCPL.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The BCPL compiler had been transported to Multics by Bell Labs and BCPL was a preferred language at Bell Labs.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Initially, a front-end program to Bell Labs' B compiler was used while a C compiler was developed.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In 1971, a new PDP-11 provided the resource to define extensions to B and rewrite the compiler.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] By 1973 the design of C language was essentially complete and the Unix kernel for a PDP-11 was rewritten in C.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Steve Johnson started development of Portable C Compiler (PCC) to support retargeting of C compilers to new machines.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Object-oriented programming (OOP) offered some interesting possibilities for application development and maintenance.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] OOP concepts go further back but were part of LISP and Simula language science.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Bell Labs became interested in OOP with the development of C++.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] C++ was first used in 1980 for systems programming.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The initial design leveraged C language systems programming abilities with Simula concepts.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Object-oriented facilities were added in 1983.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The Cfront program implemented a C++ front-end for C84 language compiler.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In subsequent years several C++ compilers were developed as C++ popularity grew.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In many application domains, the idea of using a higher-level language quickly caught on.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Because of the expanding functionality supported by newer programming languages and the increasing complexity of computer architectures, compilers became more complex.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] DARPA (Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency) sponsored a compiler project with Wulf's CMU research team in 1970.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The Production Quality Compiler-Compiler PQCC design would produce a Production Quality Compiler (PQC) from formal definitions of source language and the target.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] PQCC tried to extend the term compiler-compiler beyond the traditional meaning as a parser generator (e.g., Yacc) without much success.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] PQCC might more properly be referred to as a compiler generator.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] PQCC research into code generation process sought to build a truly automatic compiler-writing system.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The effort discovered and designed the phase structure of the PQC.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The BLISS-11 compiler provided the initial structure.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The phases included analyses (front end), intermediate translation to virtual machine (middle end), and translation to the target (back end).
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] TCOL was developed for the PQCC research to handle language specific constructs in the intermediate representation.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Variations of TCOL supported various languages.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The PQCC project investigated techniques of automated compiler construction.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The design concepts proved useful in optimizing compilers and compilers for the (since 1995, object-oriented) programming language Ada.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The Ada *STONEMAN* document formalized the program support environment (APSE) along with the kernel (KAPSE) and minimal (MAPSE).
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] An Ada interpreter NYU/ED supported development and standardization efforts with the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and the International Standards Organization (ISO).
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Initial Ada compiler development by the U.S.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Military Services included the compilers in a complete integrated design environment along the lines of the *STONEMAN* document.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Army and Navy worked on the Ada Language System (ALS) project targeted to DEC/VAX architecture while the Air Force started on the Ada Integrated Environment (AIE) targeted to IBM 370 series.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] While the projects did not provide the desired results, they did contribute to the overall effort on Ada development.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Other Ada compiler efforts got underway in Britain at the University of York and in Germany at the University of Karlsruhe.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] S., Verdix (later acquired by Rational) delivered the Verdix Ada Development System (VADS) to the Army.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] VADS provided a set of development tools including a compiler.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Unix/VADS could be hosted on a variety of Unix platforms such as DEC Ultrix and the Sun 3/60 Solaris targeted to Motorola 68020 in an Army CECOM evaluation.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] There were soon many Ada compilers available that passed the Ada Validation tests.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The Free Software Foundation GNU project developed the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) which provides a core capability to support multiple languages and targets.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The Ada version GNAT is one of the most widely used Ada compilers.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] GNAT is free but there is also commercial support, for example, AdaCore, was founded in 1994 to provide commercial software solutions for Ada.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] GNAT Pro includes the GNU GCC based GNAT with a tool suite to provide an integrated development environment.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] High-level languages continued to drive compiler research and development.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Focus areas included optimization and automatic code generation.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Trends in programming languages and development environments influenced compiler technology.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] More compilers became included in language distributions (PERL, Java Development Kit) and as a component of an IDE (VADS, Eclipse, Ada Pro).
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The interrelationship and interdependence of technologies grew.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The advent of web services promoted growth of web languages and scripting languages.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Scripts trace back to the early days of Command Line Interfaces (CLI) where the user could enter commands to be executed by the system.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] User Shell concepts developed with languages to write shell programs.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Early Windows designs offered a simple batch programming capability.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The conventional transformation of these language used an interpreter.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] While not widely used, Bash and Batch compilers have been written.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] More recently sophisticated interpreted languages became part of the developers tool kit.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Modern scripting languages include PHP, Python, Ruby and Lua.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] (Lua is widely used in game development.) All of these have interpreter and compiler support.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] "When the field of compiling began in the late 50s, its focus was limited to the translation of high-level language programs into machine code ...
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The compiler field is increasingly intertwined with other disciplines including computer architecture, programming languages, formal methods, software engineering, and computer security." The "Compiler Research: The Next 50 Years" article noted the importance of object-oriented languages and Java.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Security and parallel computing were cited among the future research targets.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] A compiler implements a formal transformation from a high-level source program to a low-level target program.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Compiler design can define an end-to-end solution or tackle a defined subset that interfaces with other compiling tools e.g., preprocessors, assemblers, linkers.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Design requirements include rigorously defined interfaces both internally between compiler components and externally between supporting toolsets.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In the early days, the approach taken to compiler design was directly affected by the complexity of the computer language to be processed, the experience of the person(s) designing it, and the resources available.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Resource limitations led to the need to pass through the source code more than once.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] A compiler for a relatively simple language written by one person might be a single, monolithic piece of software.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] However, as the source language grows in complexity the design may be split into a number of interdependent phases.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Separate phases provide design improvements that focus development on the functions in the compiling process.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Classifying compilers by number of passes has its background in the hardware resource limitations of computers.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Compiling involves performing much work and early computers did not have enough memory to contain one program that did all of this work.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] As a result, compilers were split up into smaller programs which each made a pass over the source (or some representation of it) performing some of the required analysis and translations.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The ability to compile in a single pass has classically been seen as a benefit because it simplifies the job of writing a compiler and one-pass compilers generally compile source code faster than multi-pass compilers.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Thus, partly driven by the resource limits of early systems, many early languages were specifically designed so that they could be compiled in one pass (e.g., Pascal).
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In some cases, the design of a language feature may require a compiler to perform more than one pass over the source.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For example, consider a declaration appearing on line 20 of the source which affects the translation of a statement appearing on line 10.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In this case, the first pass needs to gather information about declarations appearing after statements that they affect, with the translation then performed during a subsequent pass.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The disadvantage of compiling in a single pass is that it is not possible to perform many of the sophisticated optimizations needed to generate high quality code.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] It can be difficult to count exactly how many passes an optimizing compiler makes.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For instance, different phases of optimization may analyse one expression many times but only analyse another expression once.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Splitting a compiler up into small programs is a technique used by researchers interested in producing provably correct compilers.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Proving the correctness of a set of small programs often requires less effort than proving the correctness of a larger, single, equivalent program.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Regardless of the exact number of phases in the compiler design, the phases can be assigned to one of three stages.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The stages include a front end, a middle end, and a back end.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] This front/middle/back-end approach makes it possible to combine front ends for different languages with back ends for different CPUs while sharing the optimizations of the middle end.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Practical examples of this approach are the GNU Compiler Collection, Clang (LLVM-based C/C++ compiler), and the Amsterdam Compiler Kit, which have multiple front-ends, shared optimizations and multiple back-ends.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The front end analyzes the source code to build an internal representation of the program, called the intermediate representation (IR).
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] It also manages the symbol table, a data structure mapping each symbol in the source code to associated information such as location, type and scope.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] While the frontend can be a single monolithic function or program, as in a scannerless parser, it was traditionally implemented and analyzed as several phases, which may execute sequentially or concurrently.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] This method is favored due to its modularity and separation of concerns.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Most commonly, the frontend is broken into three phases: lexical analysis (also known as lexing or scanning), syntax analysis (also known as scanning or parsing), and semantic analysis.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Lexing and parsing comprise the syntactic analysis (word syntax and phrase syntax, respectively), and in simple cases, these modules (the lexer and parser) can be automatically generated from a grammar for the language, though in more complex cases these require manual modification.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The lexical grammar and phrase grammar are usually context-free grammars, which simplifies analysis significantly, with context-sensitivity handled at the semantic analysis phase.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The semantic analysis phase is generally more complex and written by hand, but can be partially or fully automated using attribute grammars.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] These phases themselves can be further broken down: lexing as scanning and evaluating, and parsing as building a concrete syntax tree (CST, parse tree) and then transforming it into an abstract syntax tree (AST, syntax tree).
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In some cases additional phases are used, notably *line reconstruction* and *preprocessing,* but these are rare.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The middle end, also known as *optimizer,* performs optimizations on the intermediate representation in order to improve the performance and the quality of the produced machine code.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The middle end contains those optimizations that are independent of the CPU architecture being targeted.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Compiler analysis is the prerequisite for any compiler optimization, and they tightly work together.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For example, dependence analysis is crucial for loop transformation.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The scope of compiler analysis and optimizations vary greatly; their scope may range from operating within a basic block, to whole procedures, or even the whole program.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] There is a trade-off between the granularity of the optimizations and the cost of compilation.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For example, peephole optimizations are fast to perform during compilation but only affect a small local fragment of the code, and can be performed independently of the context in which the code fragment appears.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] In contrast, interprocedural optimization requires more compilation time and memory space, but enable optimizations that are only possible by considering the behavior of multiple functions simultaneously.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Interprocedural analysis and optimizations are common in modern commercial compilers from HP, IBM, SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The free software GCC was criticized for a long time for lacking powerful interprocedural optimizations, but it is changing in this respect.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Another open source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64, which is used by many organizations for research and commercial purposes.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Due to the extra time and space needed for compiler analysis and optimizations, some compilers skip them by default.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Users have to use compilation options to explicitly tell the compiler which optimizations should be enabled.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The back end is responsible for the CPU architecture specific optimizations and for code generation.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Compiler correctness is the branch of software engineering that deals with trying to show that a compiler behaves according to its language specification.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Techniques include developing the compiler using formal methods and using rigorous testing (often called compiler validation) on an existing compiler.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Higher-level programming languages usually appear with a type of translation in mind: either designed as compiled language or interpreted language.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] However, in practice there is rarely anything about a language that *requires* it to be exclusively compiled or exclusively interpreted, although it is possible to design languages that rely on re-interpretation at run time.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The categorization usually reflects the most popular or widespread implementations of a language.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For instance, BASIC is sometimes called an interpreted language, and C a compiled one, despite the existence of BASIC compilers and C interpreters.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Interpretation does not replace compilation completely.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] It only hides it from the user and makes it gradual.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Even though an interpreter can itself be interpreted, a set of directly executed machine instructions is needed somewhere at the bottom of the execution stack (see machine language).
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Furthermore, for optimization compilers can contain interpreter functionality, and interpreters may include ahead of time compilation techniques.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For example, where an expression can be executed during compilation and the results inserted into the output program, then it prevents it having to be recalculated each time the program runs, which can greatly speed up the final program.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Modern trends toward just-in-time compilation and bytecode interpretation at times blur the traditional categorizations of compilers and interpreters even further.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Meta-tracing is an automated compiler synthesis approach which takes this further and can be used to synthesize a compiler from a language interpreter.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Some language specifications spell out that implementations *must* include a compilation facility; for example, Common Lisp.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] However, there is nothing inherent in the definition of Common Lisp that stops it from being interpreted.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] To implement these features in a compiled language, programs must usually be shipped with a runtime library that includes a version of the compiler itself.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] One classification of compilers is by the platform on which their generated code executes.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] A *native* or *hosted* compiler is one whose output is intended to directly run on the same type of computer and operating system that the compiler itself runs on.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The output of a cross compiler is designed to run on a different platform.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Cross compilers are often used when developing software for embedded systems that are not intended to support a software development environment.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The output of a compiler that produces code for a virtual machine (VM) may or may not be executed on the same platform as the compiler that produced it.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For this reason, such compilers are not usually classified as native or cross compilers.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The lower level language that is the target of a compiler may itself be a high-level programming language.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] C, viewed by some as a sort of portable assembly language, is frequently the target language of such compilers.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] For example, Cfront, the original compiler for C++, used C as its target language.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] The C code generated by such a compiler is usually not intended to be readable and maintained by humans, so indent style and creating pretty C intermediate code are ignored.
[src:swc-compiler/compiler] Some of the features of C that make it a good target language include the `#line` directive, which can be generated by the compiler to support debugging of the original source, and the wide platform support available with C compilers.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:swc-compiler/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:swc-compiler/source-to-source-compiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
[src:swc-compiler/swc-rs] SWC is an extensible Rust-based platform for the next generation of fast developer tools.
[src:swc-compiler/swc-rs] It’s used by tools like Next.js, Parcel, and Deno, as well as companies like Vercel, ByteDance, Tencent, Shopify, Trip.com, and more.
[src:swc-compiler/swc-rs] SWC can be used for both compilation and bundling.
[src:swc-compiler/swc-rs] For compilation, it takes JavaScript / TypeScript files using modern JavaScript features and outputs valid code that is supported by all major browsers.
[src:swc-compiler/swc-rs] SWC is **20x faster than Babel** on a single thread and **70x faster** on four cores.
[src:swc-compiler/swc-rs] SWC can be downloaded and used as a pre-built binary, or built from source.
[src:swc-compiler/swc-rs] Follow @kdy1dev on Twitter for future project updates.
[src:swc-compiler/swc-rs] Feel free to join the discussions on GitHub !
